{"id":"1610.03446","submitter":"Dmitriy Drusvyatskiy","authors":"Dmitriy Drusvyatskiy, Alexander D. Ioffe, Adrian S. Lewis","title":"Nonsmooth optimization using Taylor-like models: error bounds,\n  convergence, and termination criteria","comments":"23 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.OC","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We consider optimization algorithms that successively minimize simple\nTaylor-like models of the objective function. Methods of Gauss-Newton type for\nminimizing the composition of a convex function and a smooth map are common\nexamples. Our main result is an explicit relationship between the step-size of\nany such algorithm and the slope of the function at a nearby point.\nConsequently, we (1) show that the step-sizes can be reliably used to terminate\nthe algorithm, (2) prove that as long as the step-sizes tend to zero, every\nlimit point of the iterates is stationary, and (3) show that conditions, akin\nto classical quadratic growth, imply that the step-sizes linearly bound the\ndistance of the iterates to the solution set. The latter so-called error bound\nproperty is typically used to establish linear (or faster) convergence\nguarantees. Analogous results hold when the step-size is replaced by the square\nroot of the decrease in the model's value. We complete the paper with\nextensions to when the models are minimized only inexactly.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 11 Oct 2016 17:57:27 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-10-12"}
